+{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01CeHVuSBS3KkWcfABwUsDUh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Consensus is unavailable (no API keys configured). Falling back to autopilot mode where I'll make the design decisions myself based on my expertise.\n\nLet me work through the design decisions:\n\n**Q1: Algorithm for Toggle Puzzle?**\n→ Choosing: **Gaussian elimination over GF(2)**\n  Reasoning: This is a standard linear algebra problem over the binary field. Each light equation is a linear equation mod 2. Gaussian elimination is O(n^3) which handles 40x40 easily within 5 seconds. BFS/SAT are unnecessary overhead.\n\n**Q2: Algorithm for Counter Puzzle?**\n→ Choosing: **Gaussian elimination over GF(p)**\n  Reasoning: Same approach but over GF(p) where p is prime. Modular inverses exist for all non-zero elements since p is prime. Standard Gaussian elimination with modular arithmetic.\n\n**Q3: How to find minimum/lexicographically smallest solution with free variables?**\n→ Choosing: **Enumerate free variable combinations when feasible, with optimization**\n  Reasoning: After Gaussian elimination, free variables define the solution space. For GF(2) with k free variables, enumerate 2^k combinations. For GF(p), enumerate p^k combinations. If k is small (say ≤20 for GF(2), ≤8 for larger primes), this is feasible. For larger k, we need a smarter approach - but in practice, well-constrained problems rarely have many free variables. For the worst case, we can use a branch-and-bound or greedy approach.\n\nLet me now write the design document and then implement."}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1509,"cache_read_input_tokens":24255,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1509},"output_tokens":2,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id"